******
[9] DR Congo
Date: Thu 14 Feb 2019
Source: Newsday, a Daily Nation report [abridged, edited]
https://www.newsday.co.zw/2019/02/hundred-children-die-in-dr-congo-measles-outbreak/


More than 100 children in Democratic Republic of Congo [DRC] have died of measles since the start of the year [2019], an outbreak that has added to deadly epidemics of cholera and Ebola, the UN said on [Wed 13 Feb 2019].

Health officials in the southeast provinces of Lualaba and Lomami recorded 7175 cases of measles in January [2019], "at least 137 of which were fatal," the UN's MONUSCO peacekeeping mission said. More than 80% of the fatalities were children aged under 5, it said.

Experts have blamed lack of vaccination, poor medical facilities and malnutrition among the young.

MONUSCO added that 1936 cases of cholera had been recorded since the start of the year [2019] in Katanga, Lomami and Tanganyika.

Lack of clean drinking water, sanitation and medical care were hampering the fight against the disease, it said.

"We don't speak about these 2 epidemics very much" yet they are "also very worrying and deadly," said the report.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Kunihiko Iizuka

[This is a tragedy on top of the Ebola outbreak where more than 500 deaths have been recorded, of which approximately 100 are children. The high fatality rate in children from measles is likely the problem of getting the vaccine to them with all the civil unrest, and the recovery is exacerbated by malnutrition. - Mod.LK]

******
[10] Tunisia
Date: Thu 14 Feb 2019
Source: Tunisie Numerique [in French, trans Corr.SB, abridged, edited]
https://www.tunisienumerique.com/tunisie-six-morts-et-200-cas-dinfection-a-la-rougeole-selon-le-ministere-de-la-sante/


A total of 144 cases of measles in the Kasserine region, 66 cases in Sfax and isolated cases in other regions were recorded up to [Wed 13 Feb 2019], by the services of the Ministry of Health; ie 200 cases in total.

Six deaths of babies have been deplored. Their death is linked to their altered health status before they were infected with the virus, the ministry said in a statement.

The Ministry of Health epidemic follow-up called for consultation of doctors in case of symptoms, especially in babies. Patients must be isolated from the rest of the family even in doctors' waiting rooms. Schoolchildren must stay at home for a minimum of 5 days from the onset of the 1st symptoms.

[Byline: Mourad S]

